{{Infobox astronomical survey}}
[[File:CALIFA HexDR2 mandala.png|thumb|A composite of panels depicting maps of some of the properties of galaxies obtained from CALIFA data.]]
The '''CALIFA Survey''' (''Calar Alto Legacy Integral Field Area Survey'') is an astronomical project to map 600 galaxies with [[Integral field spectrograph|integral field spectroscopy (IFS)]], to allow detailed studies of these objects. The data are taken at the [[Calar Alto Observatory]] in Spain.

==Project==
The CALIFA project addresses a number of open questions in galaxy evolution, among them: 
# The chemical evolution of galaxies: how, when, and where metals are produced in galaxies  
# Galaxy masses from different tracers: how much mass there is in stars, gas, and dark matter, and how it is distributed 
# Galaxy assembly as traced from the kinematic structure: what the motions of stars and gas tell us about the structure of the galaxies 
# Galaxy assembly as traced through the stellar population content: how, when, and where did stars form throughout the history of the galaxies

CALIFA data are made public through regular releases (DR). DR1, containing 200 data cubes of 100 galaxies, was released 1 November 2012.<ref name=CALIFA-DR1>{{cite journal |title= CALIFA, the Calar Alto Legacy Integral Field Area survey. II. First public data release |author= B. Husemann |display-authors= etal |journal= Astronomy & Astrophysics |volume= 549 |id= A87 |pages= 25 pp |date= January 2013 |doi= 10.1051/0004-6361/201220582 |bibcode= 2013A&A...549A..87H |arxiv = 1210.8150 |hdl= 10261/133847 }}</ref> DR2, containing 400 data cubes of 200 galaxies, was released on 1 October 2014.<ref name=CALIFA-DR2>{{cite journal |title= CALIFA, the Calar Alto Legacy Integral Field Area survey. III. Second public data release |volume= 1409 |pages= arXiv:1409.8302 |author= R. García-Benito |display-authors= etal |date= September 2014 |bibcode= 2015A&A...576A.135G |arxiv= 1409.8302 |doi= 10.1051/0004-6361/201425080 }}</ref>

