{{Expert-subject |Viruses|reason=Confusing, difficult for non-experts to understand |date=June 2013 }}
The '''gag-onc fusion protein''' (also written as '''Gag-v-Onc''', with "v" indicating that the Onc sequence resides in a viral genome)<ref>{{cite book |title=Genes VII |last1=Lewin |first1=Benjamin |year=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=USA |isbn=978-0198792765 }}</ref> is a general term for a [[fusion protein]] formed from a [[group-specific antigen]] ('gag') gene and that of an [[oncogene]] ('onc'), a gene that plays a role in the development of a cancer. ''Onc'' is a generic placeholder for a given specific oncogene, such as [[C-jun]]. (In the case of a fusion with [[C-jun]], the resulting "gag-jun" protein is known alternatively as [[RELA|p65]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?Db=mesh&Cmd=DetailsSearch&Term=%22Oncogene+Protein+p65(gag-jun)%22%5BMeSH+Terms%5D|title=Oncogene Protein p65(gag-jun) - MeSH - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref>
Gag genes are part of a general architecture for [[Oncovirus#Description of virus|retroviruses]], viruses that replicate through [[reverse transcription]], where the gag region of the [[genome]] encodes proteins that constitute the matrix, capsid and nucleocapsid of the mature virus particles. Like in [[HIV#Replication cycle|HIV's replication cycle]], these proteins are needed for [[Viral shedding#Via budding|viral budding]] from the host cell's plasma membrane, where the fully formed [[virion]]s leave the cell to infect other cells.<ref>''Principles of Virology'', 3rd edition, Vol. 1, Molecular Biology, 2009</ref>
As a specific case, a Gag-v-Onc fusion protein from the [[Rous sarcoma virus]] is useful in illustrating the dual role that the fusion protein plays in both the viral and host cellular life cycle. For example, the viral gene [[Rous sarcoma virus#Src gene|Src]] (as in "sarcoma") is not necessary for viral reproduction, but does affect [[virulence]]. Due to evidence<ref name="pmid6273838">{{cite journal | author = Smart JE, Oppermann H, Czernilofsky AP, Purchio AF, Erikson RL, Bishop JM | title = Characterization of sites for tyrosine phosphorylation in the transforming protein of Rous sarcoma virus (pp60v-src) and its normal cellular homologue (pp60c-src) | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 78 | issue = 10 | pages = 6013–7 |date=October 1981 | pmid = 6273838 | pmc = 348967 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.78.10.6013}}</ref> of conserved [[Homology (biology)|homology]] between the [[v-Src]] gene and its host (animal) genomes, and its non-essential status for viral reproduction, the v-Src gene is likely to have been acquired from a host genome and altered by subsequent mutations.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1073/pnas.80.9.2519 | last1 = Swanstrom | first1 = R. | last2 = Parker | first2 = R. C. | last3 = Varmus | first3 = H. E. | last4 = Bishop | first4 = J. M. | title = Transduction of a cellular oncogene: The genesis of Rous sarcoma virus | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 80 | issue = 9 | pages = 2519–2523 | year = 1983 | pmid = 6302692 | pmc = 393857 }}</ref> These subsequent mutations are responsible for the oncogenic capabilities of the virus, as the normal (host) version of the Src gene, [[C-src tyrosine kinase|c-Src]] promotes survival, [[angiogenesis]], [[Cell growth|proliferation]] and invasion pathways. These native pathways are disrupted in the presence of the mutant Src gene (v-Src) such that oncogenesis becomes more likely for the infected host cells, since the v-Src gene is [[Translation (biology)|translated]] into a functionally distinct version of its host counterpart.
When a viral gene is introduced into the host cell and is sufficient to induce oncogenesis – the creation of cancerous cells – in the infected cell line, the gene is said to be a "viral transforming gene".<ref name="Amazon-1555814808">{{cite book |title=Principles of Virology, Vol. 2: Pathogenesis and Control |isbn=978-1-55581-480-9 |date=December 1, 2008 |publisher=ASM Press |edition=3 |first=S. Jane |last=Flint}}</ref> When this type of gene is [[Translation (biology)|translated]] to a protein, the protein is called a "transforming protein". Note that since the viral oncogenes originated from a host genome, the transformation event is different from [[Transduction (genetics)#More general uses of the term|transduction]], which describes the process of introducing non-native genes to a host organism via a viral infection.
In the case of the [[murine leukemia virus]]es, a species of viruses capable of causing cancer in [[murine]]s (mice), the viral life cycle can also be responsible for oncogenesis through a Gag-v-Onc fusion protein called "Mo-MuLV(src)", which is a Gag-v-Src protein capable of inducing oncogenesis in living mice.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Feuerman | first1 = M. H. | last2 = Lee | first2 = W. T. | last3 = Pattengale | first3 = P. K. | last4 = Fan | first4 = H. | title = Comparison of three recombinant murine leukemia viruses carrying the v-src oncogene of avian sarcoma virus: Differences in in vitro transformation and in vivo pathogenicity | journal = Molecular Carcinogenesis | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 57–66 | year = 1988 | pmid = 2855603 }}</ref>
