'''''The Aleppo Codex: A True Story of Obsession, Faith, and the Pursuit of an Ancient Bible''''' is a 2012 book by [[Matti Friedman]] published by Algonquin. [[File:Aleppo Codex (Deut).jpg|thumb|150px|Page from Aleppo Codex]] The book tells the story of how the [[Aleppo codex]], one of the world's oldest extant [[Bible]]s , was saved from destruction during the [[1947 Anti-Jewish riots in Aleppo|1947 Aleppo pogrom]], how it was smuggled into Israel, and what became of the missing pages.<ref name="BergmanWhodonit">{{cite news|last1=Bergman|first1=Ronen|title=A High Holy Whodunit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/29/magazine/the-aleppo-codex-mystery.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=25 July 2012}}</ref> The ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' calls Friedman's book "a detective thriller," noting that, "not everything about the codex is as it seems."<ref name="BalintRival">{{cite news|last1=Balint|first1=Benjamin|title=Rival Owners, Sacred Text (book review)|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303918204577448610210896018|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=12 June 2013}}</ref>
==Prizes== ''The Aleppo Codex'' won the 2014 [[Sami Rohr Prize for Jewish Literature]],<ref>{{cite news |date=22 January 2014 |title=Friedman accepts ‘Aleppo Codex’ prize |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/friedman-accepts-prize-for-aleppo-codex/ |newspaper=The Times of Israel }}</ref> was selected as one of [[Booklist]]'s top ten religion and spirituality books of 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.booklistonline.com/Top-10-Religion-Spirituality-Books-Ilene-Cooper/pid=5791762 |title=Top 10 Religion & Spirituality Books |date=15 November 2012 |publisher=Booklist }}</ref> was awarded the [[American Library Association]]'s 2013 Sophie Brody Medal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2013/01/aleppo-codex-wins-rusa%E2%80%99s-sophie-brody-medal-achievement-jewish-literature-3 |title='The Aleppo Codex' wins RUSA’s Sophie Brody Medal for achievement in Jewish literature |date=27 January 2013 |publisher=American Library Association }}</ref> and the 2013 [[Canadian Jewish Book Awards|Canadian Jewish Book Award]] for history,<ref>{{cite news |date=2 May 2013 |title=‘Aleppo Codex’ wins Canadian book award |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/aleppo-codex-wins-canadian-book-award/ |newspaper=The Times of Israel }}</ref> and received second place for the [[Religion Newswriters Association]]'s 2013 nonfiction religion book of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rna.org/?page=2013_contest_archive |title=2013 RNA Contest Winners |date= |publisher=Religion Newswriters Association }}</ref>
